699
00:54:22,323 --> 00:54:22,864
[SPEAKER_06]: Absolutely.

700
00:54:22,904 --> 00:54:30,862
[SPEAKER_06]: So people who take more than three return international flights a year, those frequent flyers would pay more under our plans.

701
00:54:30,922 --> 00:54:37,156
[SPEAKER_06]: And it is those people who take the many, many, many flights that we need to target with those.

702
00:54:37,257 --> 00:54:37,918
[SPEAKER_06]: Richard Tyson.

703
00:54:37,898 --> 00:54:40,100
[SPEAKER_14]: There are two immediate things that we should be doing.

704
00:54:40,140 --> 00:54:50,312
[SPEAKER_14]: We should be doing, as a country, we should be leading the way globally with a worldwide initiative to plant hundreds and hundreds of millions of trees to capture CO2.

705
00:54:50,712 --> 00:54:58,921
[SPEAKER_14]: The next thing we should do is we need to invest in major technology, green technology, so that we can capture CO2 and reduce CO2 emissions.

706
00:54:58,941 --> 00:55:03,767
[SPEAKER_14]: There's one more thing that we don't talk enough about, and that is recycling our own waste.

707
00:55:03,787 --> 00:55:06,910
[SPEAKER_14]: My son in Asia, he rang me up in horror

708
00:55:06,890 --> 00:55:13,936
[SPEAKER_14]: when he saw, and he was clearing up, piles and piles of plastic bottles on beaches in Asia, and where did they come from?

709
00:55:14,357 --> 00:55:15,678
[SPEAKER_14]: Supermarkets in Britain.

710
00:55:15,898 --> 00:55:17,700
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to recycle our own waste.

711
00:55:17,720 --> 00:55:28,790
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, forgive me, politicians, but when all politicians agree that something's very serious, and all of them agree that it can be done without much pain, people often think, well, can that really be true?

712
00:55:28,850 --> 00:55:35,195
[SPEAKER_04]: Here is... Who's willing to say, actually, you know what, your lifestyles will have to change, something will have to give?

713
00:55:35,676 --> 00:55:36,897
[SPEAKER_10]: Nicola Sturgeon, will you?

714
00:55:36,877 --> 00:55:49,461
[SPEAKER_10]: I think people's lifestyles do have to change, but I also think governments and industry has to take the lead, because there's a relatively small number of companies across the world that are responsible for a disproportionate amount of emissions.

715
00:55:49,521 --> 00:55:55,513
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, again, this is one of the areas where I say, look at what my government is doing, not just on what we're promising.

716
00:55:55,533 --> 00:55:58,058
[SPEAKER_10]: We've got the toughest targets anywhere in the world.

717
00:55:58,038 --> 00:56:02,964
[SPEAKER_10]: 75% of Scotland's electricity already comes from renewable sources.

718
00:56:03,284 --> 00:56:07,690
[SPEAKER_10]: Last year, we planted 84% of all of the trees planted in the UK.

719
00:56:07,730 --> 00:56:09,973
[SPEAKER_10]: We're in Scotland, 22 million trees.

720
00:56:10,293 --> 00:56:13,877
[SPEAKER_10]: We're about to invest half a billion pounds in new bus infrastructure.

721
00:56:13,897 --> 00:56:16,100
[SPEAKER_04]: Would you stop all new oil drilling in Scotland?

722
00:56:16,140 --> 00:56:18,443
[SPEAKER_04]: Because people would argue fossil fuels should go.

723
00:56:18,423 --> 00:56:19,625
[SPEAKER_10]: We have to move away from that.

724
00:56:19,645 --> 00:56:26,133
[SPEAKER_10]: The reason you can't do it immediately without reducing demand is that you'd make yourself more reliant on imports, which would increase your carbon emissions.

725
00:56:26,173 --> 00:56:29,838
[SPEAKER_10]: But the transition away from fossil fuels is important and is underway.

726
00:56:29,938 --> 00:56:30,479
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you very much.

727
00:56:30,499 --> 00:56:30,919
[SPEAKER_12]: Rishi Sunder.

728
00:56:31,780 --> 00:56:37,628
[SPEAKER_12]: Tabitha, I'm not sure how old your pupils are, but my younger daughter's seven, and she's the climate change champion in our house.

729
00:56:37,648 --> 00:56:42,534
[SPEAKER_12]: And she brings home how important this is in all those practical everyday ways that you were talking about, the immediate steps.

730
00:56:42,814 --> 00:56:44,076
[SPEAKER_12]: She turns off all the lights.

731
00:56:44,056 --> 00:56:51,088
[SPEAKER_12]: She makes sure that the tap is off when she's brushing her teeth and she's going through making sure that everything goes in the right recycling bin.

732
00:56:51,109 --> 00:56:53,352
[SPEAKER_12]: And now there are more than one recycling bin.

733
00:56:53,393 --> 00:56:55,035
[SPEAKER_12]: So those are all the practical immediate things.

734
00:56:55,336 --> 00:57:03,270
[SPEAKER_12]: But for the government the most important thing for us to do if we have a strong economy we can then invest in innovation because ultimately it's going to be innovation.

735
00:57:03,310 --> 00:57:04,933
[SPEAKER_12]: It's going to be cheaper car batteries.

736
00:57:04,913 --> 00:57:09,440
[SPEAKER_12]: new forms of renewable offshore wind or, indeed, green infrastructure that solve this problem.

737
00:57:09,740 --> 00:57:14,828
[SPEAKER_12]: We can only make those investments if we have a strong economy and that's something that we're very, very committed to.

738
00:57:14,848 --> 00:57:15,209
[SPEAKER_11]: Rebecca Lockhart.

739
00:57:15,229 --> 00:57:15,809
[SPEAKER_11]: Caroline Lucas, briefly.

740
00:57:15,829 --> 00:57:25,344
[SPEAKER_11]: Can you explain to her the fact that your government has been slashing support to renewable energies, that flogged off the Green Investment Bank, that has made it harder to have onshore wind in this country.

741
00:57:25,624 --> 00:57:29,470
[SPEAKER_11]: Your track record on climate and the environment is abysmal.

742
00:57:29,450 --> 00:57:32,553
[SPEAKER_12]: Let's look at that record.

743
00:57:32,593 --> 00:57:37,898
[SPEAKER_12]: We've decarbonised our economy faster than any other major economy in the world.

744
00:57:37,918 --> 00:57:38,799
[SPEAKER_12]: By outsourcing everything to China.

745
00:57:38,819 --> 00:57:43,824
[SPEAKER_12]: We've been the first to phase out coal, and we are leading the world in banning single-use plastics.

746
00:57:43,984 --> 00:57:46,306
[SPEAKER_12]: It's actually a record that I'm very proud to stand here on.

747
00:57:46,506 --> 00:57:47,768
[SPEAKER_12]: And we talk about renewable energy.

748
00:57:48,008 --> 00:57:50,250
[SPEAKER_12]: We are now the world leader in offshore wind.

749
00:57:50,490 --> 00:57:52,412
[SPEAKER_12]: That is something that this government has supported.

750
00:57:52,432 --> 00:57:52,892
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much.

751
00:57:52,953 --> 00:57:54,194
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you, Rebecca Long-Bailey.

752
00:57:54,254 --> 00:57:55,575
[SPEAKER_12]: Rebecca Long-Bailey, please.

753
00:57:55,555 --> 00:58:08,411
[SPEAKER_05]: I think Rishi's heart is in the right place but his party is led by a Prime Minister who called climate change a primitive fear without foundation and the policies that they have driven forward so far underline his true belief in this.

754
00:58:08,812 --> 00:58:10,577
[SPEAKER_05]: But ultimately this election

755
00:58:10,557 --> 00:58:13,020
[SPEAKER_05]: is critical to tackle the climate crisis.

756
00:58:13,321 --> 00:58:14,643
[SPEAKER_05]: We are running out of time.

757
00:58:14,703 --> 00:58:21,933
[SPEAKER_05]: The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change have said that we have to take the vast majority of action to decarbonise our economy by 2030.

758
00:58:22,634 --> 00:58:28,903
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's why we've rolled out a very detailed Green Industrial Revolution to outline how we're going to do that.

759
00:58:28,883 --> 00:58:29,524
[SPEAKER_15]: Adam Price.

760
00:58:29,544 --> 00:58:31,609
[SPEAKER_15]: OK, what could we do immediately?

761
00:58:31,629 --> 00:58:32,791
[SPEAKER_15]: We could pass a Clean Air Act.

762
00:58:34,214 --> 00:58:35,778
[SPEAKER_15]: The Welsh Labour government could do it here.

763
00:58:35,798 --> 00:58:41,610
[SPEAKER_15]: We would take them to court because the 2,000 people, 200 in this city, that die unnecessarily because of pollution in air.

764
00:58:41,991 --> 00:58:43,013
[SPEAKER_15]: We could do that now.

765
00:58:43,093 --> 00:58:45,458
[SPEAKER_15]: Your party could do that now, Rebecca.

766
00:58:45,438 --> 00:58:46,920
[SPEAKER_15]: We are going to bring in a clean air act.

767
00:58:46,940 --> 00:58:48,462
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah, but you're saying you're doing England.

768
00:58:48,482 --> 00:58:49,985
[SPEAKER_15]: You're in government here in Wales.

769
00:58:50,025 --> 00:58:52,168
[SPEAKER_15]: People will judge you, not by your words, but your deeds.

770
00:58:52,188 --> 00:58:53,109
[SPEAKER_15]: You're not doing it here.

771
00:58:53,450 --> 00:58:57,936
[SPEAKER_15]: We could actually massively improve the level of procurement of local food.

772
00:58:57,956 --> 00:59:08,391
[SPEAKER_15]: You know, our hospitals, our schools that are buying imported food, when we could actually be supporting local food systems, helping our environment and our economy as well.

773
00:59:08,371 --> 00:59:12,078
[SPEAKER_04]: Forgive me, Adam, we've got to keep moving because we've got lots of subjects that we still want to get through.

774
00:59:12,098 --> 00:59:17,649
[SPEAKER_04]: I know it's a huge topic and it's frustrating to move on, but we do want to talk about the National Health Service tonight.

775
00:59:17,689 --> 00:59:19,112
[SPEAKER_04]: Lucy Taylor is with us.

776
00:59:19,152 --> 00:59:21,236
[SPEAKER_04]: Lucy, from Cardiff.

777
00:59:21,257 --> 00:59:25,024
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm studying pharmacy and I'm genuinely worried about what my future will look like.

778
00:59:25,485 --> 00:59:26,808
[SPEAKER_07]: The NHS is failing.

779
00:59:27,068 --> 00:59:30,615
[SPEAKER_07]: What are you going to do to stop this and make sure it's not sold to the highest bidder?

780
00:59:31,523 --> 00:59:33,285
[SPEAKER_04]: Lucy is studying pharmacy.

781
00:59:33,325 --> 00:59:33,986
[SPEAKER_04]: What are you doing?

782
00:59:34,046 --> 00:59:37,710
[SPEAKER_04]: Two-part question to deal with the fact the NHS, in her words, is failing.

783
00:59:38,511 --> 00:59:42,555
[SPEAKER_04]: And what will you do to ensure it is not sold off to the highest bidder?

784
00:59:42,575 --> 00:59:44,197
[SPEAKER_04]: Rishi Sunak.

785
00:59:44,217 --> 00:59:46,519
[SPEAKER_12]: Lucy, I grew up in an NHS family.

786
00:59:46,579 --> 00:59:49,142
[SPEAKER_12]: Dad was a GP and my mum was a pharmacist.

787
00:59:49,583 --> 00:59:59,313
[SPEAKER_12]: I spent my entire childhood working in her pharmacy and I saw firsthand what an unbelievable difference the NHS made to my parents' patients and their lives.

788
00:59:59,333 --> 01:00:01,075
[SPEAKER_12]: They became part of our family.

789
01:00:01,055 --> 01:00:06,843
[SPEAKER_12]: And that's why I and my party are deeply committed to the NHS and investing in it.

790
01:00:07,244 --> 01:00:09,988
[SPEAKER_12]: We've outlined a plan for £34 billion more.

791
01:00:10,048 --> 01:00:17,759
[SPEAKER_12]: That will go on putting 50,000 nurses on our wards, 50 million more GP appointments and new and upgraded hospitals.

792
01:00:18,160 --> 01:00:29,256
[SPEAKER_12]: But I say this, it's because we all care so deeply about the NHS that we must get Brexit done so that we can focus on it properly and give it the support and the investment that it deserves.

793
01:00:29,236 --> 01:00:35,024
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's focus on what she said, which is, how will you ensure it isn't sold to the highest bidder?

794
01:00:35,205 --> 01:00:39,130
[SPEAKER_12]: The NHS is not for sale, never has been, and never will be.

795
01:00:39,852 --> 01:00:42,095
[SPEAKER_04]: OK. Rebecca Long-Bailey, you've heard him say that.

796
01:00:42,155 --> 01:00:44,178
[SPEAKER_04]: You've heard the Prime Minister say that.

797
01:00:44,198 --> 01:00:47,042
[SPEAKER_04]: Why do you insist on claiming that it is for sale?

798
01:00:47,022 --> 01:00:51,292
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, I mean, this government has been in place for 10 years now.

799
01:00:51,372 --> 01:00:53,618
[SPEAKER_05]: We don't trust a word they say on the NHS.

800
01:00:53,638 --> 01:00:57,346
[SPEAKER_05]: We've got 4.4 million people on waiting lists to have operations.

801
01:00:57,387 --> 01:01:00,735
[SPEAKER_05]: My husband was one of them, who had his operation cancelled yesterday.

802
01:01:00,775 --> 01:01:04,343
[SPEAKER_05]: But on the issue of the NHS being up for sale, documents were released...

803
01:01:04,363 --> 01:01:04,544
[SPEAKER_05]: It's not.

804
01:01:04,564 --> 01:01:04,744
[SPEAKER_05]: Come on.

805
01:01:04,724 --> 01:01:06,326
[SPEAKER_05]: I'll be honest with people, it's not up for sale.

806
01:01:06,447 --> 01:01:07,829
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's only be polite to let me finish.

807
01:01:07,849 --> 01:01:08,630
[SPEAKER_05]: Stop scaremongering.

808
01:01:08,650 --> 01:01:19,926
[SPEAKER_05]: Documents were released this week that showed very clearly that the government had been involved in numerous discussions with US trade officials where the NHS services, as it was referred to, were on the table.

809
01:01:19,946 --> 01:01:20,387
[SPEAKER_05]: Richard Tice.

810
01:01:20,407 --> 01:01:20,948
[SPEAKER_05]: This is ludicrous.

811
01:01:20,968 --> 01:01:22,530
[SPEAKER_14]: This is ludicrous.

812
01:01:22,510 --> 01:01:27,157
[SPEAKER_14]: The Labour Party clearly don't understand the difference between buying and selling.

813
01:01:27,538 --> 01:01:36,331
[SPEAKER_14]: The NHS buys lots of products, beds, curtains, sheets, drugs, all sorts of things from private providers.

814
01:01:36,831 --> 01:01:38,334
[SPEAKER_14]: Nothing is for sale in the NHS.

815
01:01:38,674 --> 01:01:42,420
