[SPEAKER_04]: The headline figure is for cutting back.

1028
01:18:26,972 --> 01:18:28,616
[SPEAKER_04]: You ask different questions, you get different answers.

1029
01:18:28,636 --> 01:18:29,979
[SPEAKER_04]: That's perfectly reasonable.

1030
01:18:30,039 --> 01:18:32,445
[SPEAKER_12]: Under the Conservatives, immigration will be lower.

1031
01:18:32,425 --> 01:18:35,191
[SPEAKER_12]: more important than the numbers is having control.

1032
01:18:35,532 --> 01:18:40,522
[SPEAKER_12]: It's about us being in charge of who's coming to this country on the basis of what they offer.

1033
01:18:40,783 --> 01:18:45,533
[SPEAKER_12]: And that's the opportunity we will have when we leave the EU and introduce our own system.

1034
01:18:45,553 --> 01:18:46,956
[SPEAKER_04]: Will it be lower under Labour, Rebecca Lombardi?

1035
01:18:46,976 --> 01:18:47,557
[SPEAKER_12]: We will have control.

1036
01:18:47,738 --> 01:18:49,742
[SPEAKER_12]: We don't want to perpetuate unlimited.

1037
01:18:49,722 --> 01:18:56,251
[SPEAKER_05]: I think this is really, really irresponsible from the Chief Secretary of the Treasury who is responsible for our economy.

1038
01:18:56,392 --> 01:19:10,632
[SPEAKER_05]: Many of the businesses that I meet can't access the skills they need or they simply don't have workers in the area that will do the types of work that they need to be carried out, whether you're looking at the hospitality sector in certain parts of the UK, whether you're looking at the farming industry.

1039
01:19:10,973 --> 01:19:16,000
[SPEAKER_05]: We need migrant labour to assist our economy and we need to have a sense

1040
01:19:15,980 --> 01:19:31,508
[SPEAKER_05]: to be

1041
01:19:31,488 --> 01:19:34,654
[SPEAKER_14]: So you want uncontrolled, unlimited immigration?

1042
01:19:34,674 --> 01:19:40,264
[SPEAKER_05]: No, we want a sensible immigration system that works in the interest of business and our economy.

1043
01:19:40,324 --> 01:19:41,787
[SPEAKER_05]: Richard Tice first.

1044
01:19:41,807 --> 01:19:43,710
[SPEAKER_14]: Richard Tice briefly.

1045
01:19:43,790 --> 01:19:52,045
[SPEAKER_14]: Unlimited immigration in the last 15 years has depressed wages and that I don't think is in the interest of the British people.

1046
01:19:52,025 --> 01:19:57,974
[SPEAKER_10]: First of all, there hasn't been unlimited immigration and it doesn't cut wages.

1047
01:19:58,274 --> 01:20:10,573
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't want to see a cut in inward migration because it would damage the economy of my country and one of the reasons I want Scotland to be independent is so we can take these decisions for ourselves rather than having damaging decisions imposed upon us.

1048
01:20:10,553 --> 01:20:11,555
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm sorry to wind it up.

1049
01:20:11,575 --> 01:20:12,839
[SPEAKER_04]: I know there's a lot you could talk about.

1050
01:20:12,859 --> 01:20:14,643
[SPEAKER_04]: We want to fit one more question in.

1051
01:20:14,663 --> 01:20:15,966
[SPEAKER_15]: Adam Price, very, very briefly.

1052
01:20:15,986 --> 01:20:18,973
[SPEAKER_15]: It's not migration that has depressed wages over the last 15 years.

1053
01:20:19,254 --> 01:20:22,622
[SPEAKER_15]: It's the austerity politics of your partners, the Conservative Party.

1054
01:20:26,467 --> 01:20:31,335
[SPEAKER_04]: You're more than welcome to stay here for another hour and a half afterwards, but we haven't got time while we're on air, at least.

1055
01:20:31,355 --> 01:20:35,381
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's move to our last question, and it comes from Trevor Morgan.

1056
01:20:35,461 --> 01:20:36,322
[SPEAKER_04]: Where is Trevor Morgan?

1057
01:20:36,342 --> 01:20:36,823
[SPEAKER_03]: Good evening.

1058
01:20:37,725 --> 01:20:40,890
[SPEAKER_03]: Donald Trump has recently confirmed his visit to the UK.

1059
01:20:41,430 --> 01:20:44,415
[SPEAKER_03]: If you had 30 seconds with him, what would you say?

1060
01:20:44,535 --> 01:20:48,521
[SPEAKER_04]: And you have only got 30 seconds each to answer this, at the most.

1061
01:20:48,541 --> 01:20:49,323
[SPEAKER_04]: Nicola Sturgeon?

1062
01:20:49,343 --> 01:20:50,124
[SPEAKER_11]: Please stand down.

1063
01:20:50,865 --> 01:20:54,010
[SPEAKER_04]: OK. Caroline Lucas, what would you say to Donald Trump?

1064
01:20:54,428 --> 01:20:59,535
[SPEAKER_11]: I would say to him that look at the US states that are actually moving in the right direction on climate change.

1065
01:20:59,555 --> 01:21:01,458
[SPEAKER_11]: It's good for the economy as well as good for the environment.

1066
01:21:01,478 --> 01:21:03,721
[SPEAKER_11]: Get your act together and get back into the Paris Agreement.

1067
01:21:03,741 --> 01:21:04,122
[SPEAKER_04]: Rishi Sunak?

1068
01:21:04,602 --> 01:21:05,383
[SPEAKER_04]: Happy Thanksgiving.

1069
01:21:06,885 --> 01:21:07,827
[SPEAKER_04]: Rebecca Long-Bailey?

1070
01:21:07,867 --> 01:21:16,158
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm a good Catholic, so I won't say in public what I probably would say to him, but the most important point I'd make is about the climate emergency and how he needs to change his position.

1071
01:21:16,218 --> 01:21:22,427
[SPEAKER_05]: There is a real climate emergency, and if we don't take action now, we're not going to leave a world or a future for our children.

1072
01:21:22,508 --> 01:21:23,249
[SPEAKER_14]: Richard Tice.

1073
01:21:23,529 --> 01:21:25,692
[SPEAKER_14]: Let's get a quick trade deal done.

1074
01:21:26,113 --> 01:21:28,316
[SPEAKER_10]: And here's our NHS, is what he would say.

1075
01:21:28,336 --> 01:21:28,596
[SPEAKER_10]: Oh, nonsense.

1076
01:21:28,616 --> 01:21:29,738
[SPEAKER_14]: Stop this scandal.

1077
01:21:29,838 --> 01:21:30,579
[SPEAKER_14]: It's pathetic.

1078
01:21:31,260 --> 01:21:33,082
[SPEAKER_14]: Just lying to the British people continually.

1079
01:21:33,142 --> 01:21:33,543
[SPEAKER_10]: It's pathetic.

1080
01:21:33,623 --> 01:21:34,864
[SPEAKER_10]: I think you've got form on that.

1081
01:21:36,046 --> 01:21:39,871
[SPEAKER_15]: Adam Bright.

1082
01:21:40,692 --> 01:21:42,795
[SPEAKER_15]: Resign and take Boris with you.

1083
01:21:48,547 --> 01:22:05,003
[SPEAKER_06]: Well I could congratulate him on getting his wish which was of course for him to have Boris Johnson and Nigel Farage come together but of course that's not going to be any good for our country so I would like to tell him that the British public still have the chance to stop him getting what he wants.

1084
01:22:05,236 --> 01:22:06,619
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you very much indeed.

1085
01:22:06,679 --> 01:22:09,405
[SPEAKER_04]: Let's move then to our closing statements.

1086
01:22:10,066 --> 01:22:17,401
[SPEAKER_04]: Each speaker has got just 30 seconds, and as with the opening statements, the order was decided before tonight by the drawing of lots.

1087
01:22:18,042 --> 01:22:23,734
[SPEAKER_04]: First, with her closing statement tonight, the Shadow Business Secretary, Labour's Rebecca Long-Bailey.

1088
01:22:24,338 --> 01:22:26,763
[SPEAKER_05]: I want to thank everybody for watching tonight.

1089
01:22:27,003 --> 01:22:29,548
[SPEAKER_05]: And it's easy to be cynical about politics.

1090
01:22:30,109 --> 01:22:32,754
[SPEAKER_05]: But politics makes real change happen.

1091
01:22:33,215 --> 01:22:34,819
[SPEAKER_05]: Labour made the NHS happen.

1092
01:22:35,179 --> 01:22:37,664
[SPEAKER_05]: We made the minimum wage and Sure Start happen.

1093
01:22:37,945 --> 01:22:40,710
[SPEAKER_05]: We'll make the Green Industrial Revolution happen.

1094
01:22:40,690 --> 01:22:43,293
[SPEAKER_05]: A vote for Labour is a vote for hope.

1095
01:22:43,753 --> 01:22:47,778
[SPEAKER_05]: For a government that supports you and invests in your community.

1096
01:22:47,798 --> 01:22:50,141
[SPEAKER_05]: A government that is on your side.

1097
01:22:50,641 --> 01:22:54,185
[SPEAKER_05]: So let's transform our country so that it works for everyone.

1098
01:22:54,566 --> 01:22:56,848
[SPEAKER_05]: Vote Labour on the 12th of December.

1099
01:22:57,609 --> 01:22:58,770
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you very much indeed.

1100
01:22:58,830 --> 01:23:02,935
[SPEAKER_04]: And next, the First Minister of Scotland, Nicola Sturgeon, the leader of the SNP.

1101
01:23:03,455 --> 01:23:08,462
[SPEAKER_10]: Boris Johnson's Tories are unfit for office, in my opinion.

1102
01:23:08,882 --> 01:23:20,077
[SPEAKER_10]: But unless people vote to keep them out, we could be stuck with them and their policies for years to come, with dire consequences for our economy and public services, especially the NHS.

1103
01:23:20,497 --> 01:23:24,703
[SPEAKER_10]: In Scotland, the SNP is the main challenger in every single Tory-held seat.

1104
01:23:24,683 --> 01:23:38,878
[SPEAKER_10]: So I vote for the SNP on December the 12th as I vote to lock Boris Johnson out of Downing Street, provide an escape route from the mess of Brexit and to put Scotland's future into Scotland's hands so that we can build a better, fairer country.

1105
01:23:39,010 --> 01:23:40,172
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you very much indeed.

1106
01:23:40,233 --> 01:23:43,840
[SPEAKER_04]: Next to the leader of Plaid Cymru, Adam Price.

1107
01:23:44,502 --> 01:23:57,289
[SPEAKER_15]: On the 13th of December, my 84-year-old father may wake up for the 11th time in his life to a Tory government he, like the majority here, old miner that he is, has never voted for.

1108
01:23:57,269 --> 01:24:05,302
[SPEAKER_15]: He stopped voting Labour 2 some years ago because he realised that change will only ever come when Wales finds its voice.

1109
01:24:05,983 --> 01:24:13,235
[SPEAKER_15]: I really hope this is that moment for my father's generation, for my son's generation, for all our generations.

1110
01:24:13,816 --> 01:24:22,129
[SPEAKER_15]: Because it's when we find our voice that we will change this nation, that Wales will build a future that is better than our past.

1111
01:24:22,463 --> 01:24:23,425
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you very much indeed.

1112
01:24:23,465 --> 01:24:28,793
[SPEAKER_04]: Now to the leader of the Liberal Democrat Party, Jo Swinson.

1113
01:24:28,813 --> 01:24:42,075
[SPEAKER_06]: As you sit on your sofa with your cup of tea, watching this election unfold, you might be thinking, surely we deserve better than this depressing duo of Boris Johnson and Jeremy Corbyn.

1114
01:24:42,241 --> 01:24:45,706
[SPEAKER_06]: Boris Johnson, caught lying again and again.

1115
01:24:46,026 --> 01:24:48,209
[SPEAKER_06]: He thinks the rules don't apply to him.

1116
01:24:48,690 --> 01:24:51,413
[SPEAKER_06]: And frankly, he only cares about himself.

1117
01:24:52,094 --> 01:24:56,260
[SPEAKER_06]: He doesn't deserve to win a majority and the Liberal Democrats can stop him.

1118
01:24:56,760 --> 01:25:00,886
[SPEAKER_06]: You have the power to stop Brexit and create a brighter future.

1119
01:25:01,366 --> 01:25:02,788
[SPEAKER_06]: Vote Liberal Democrat.

1120
01:25:03,189 --> 01:25:03,589
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

1121
01:25:03,609 --> 01:25:07,995
[SPEAKER_04]: For the Conservatives, the Chief Secretary to the Treasury, Rishi Sunak.

1122
01:25:08,667 --> 01:25:09,988
[SPEAKER_12]: This is the choice you have.

1123
01:25:10,609 --> 01:25:16,474
[SPEAKER_12]: Boris Johnson, delivering Brexit in weeks and focusing on the NHS, schools and police.

1124
01:25:17,334 --> 01:25:26,102
[SPEAKER_12]: Or Jeremy Corbyn, ridiculously stuck in neutral on one of the biggest questions our country has ever faced.

1125
01:25:26,943 --> 01:25:31,987
[SPEAKER_12]: Only the Conservatives can break this deadlock and set Britain free.

1126
01:25:32,748 --> 01:25:33,849
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you very much indeed.

1127
01:25:33,929 --> 01:25:37,712
[SPEAKER_04]: Now to the Chairman of the Brexit Party, Richard Tice.

1128
01:25:37,692 --> 01:25:40,419
[SPEAKER_14]: Brexit done right is an amazing opportunity.

1129
01:25:40,459 --> 01:25:42,965
[SPEAKER_14]: Let's go for it with ambition, with energy.

1130
01:25:43,506 --> 01:25:51,145
[SPEAKER_14]: Lower prices, higher wages, training our own people, building roads and rail projects all over the country.

1131
01:25:51,243 --> 01:25:56,833
[SPEAKER_14]: But make your vote count to get Brexit and stop Corbyn bankrupting the country.

1132
01:25:57,394 --> 01:26:02,103
[SPEAKER_14]: Only the Brexit Party can take on Labour in seats Tories have not won in decades.

1133
01:26:02,123 --> 01:26:04,628
[SPEAKER_14]: Together, let's change politics for good.

1134
01:26:05,329 --> 01:26:05,950
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you very much.

1135
01:26:06,030 --> 01:26:08,695
[SPEAKER_04]: And finally tonight, Caroline Lucas of the Green Party.

1136
01:26:09,080 --> 01:26:12,704
[SPEAKER_11]: This is the most important general election in generations.

1137
01:26:13,285 --> 01:26:16,388
[SPEAKER_11]: The last chance to remain in the EU and transform Britain.

1138
01:26:17,049 --> 01:26:19,852
[SPEAKER_11]: The very last chance to prevent runaway climate chaos.

1139
01:26:20,633 --> 01:26:25,819
[SPEAKER_11]: A half of all voters say that climate breakdown will influence their choice on December the 12th.

1140
01:26:26,520 --> 01:26:31,125
[SPEAKER_11]: Voting with them is the only way to get more Green MPs and to keep up the pressure.

1141
01:26:31,726 --> 01:26:35,290
[SPEAKER_11]: So if you've ever thought about voting Green, do it.

1142
01:26:35,310 --> 01:26:37,753
[SPEAKER_11]: If not now, when?

1143
01:26:38,290 --> 01:26:39,615
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you very much indeed.

1144
01:26:39,635 --> 01:26:45,921
[SPEAKER_04]: And ladies and gentlemen, could you thank all the politicians from the seven parties that are here tonight?

1145
01:26:50,778 --> 01:26:53,522
[SPEAKER_04]: Now, the truth is you know that the debate is never over.

1146
01:26:53,542 --> 01:26:57,447
[SPEAKER_04]: The questions you wish had been asked, questions you wish had been answered.

1147
01:26:57,947 --> 01:26:59,529
[SPEAKER_04]: And the debate now moves to you.

1148
01:26:59,589 --> 01:27:05,197
[SPEAKER_04]: It continues over on Five Live right now, where Stephen Nolan is standing by, ready to take your calls.

1149
01:27:05,257 --> 01:27:13,107
[SPEAKER_04]: Have your say on what you've heard in tonight's debate by calling 08085 909693.

1150
01:27:13,188 --> 01:27:22,920
[SPEAKER_04]: Next Friday on BBC One, I'll be hosting Boris Johnson versus Jeremy Corbyn in the BBC Prime Ministerial debate, just six days before polling day.

1151
01:27:23,421 --> 01:27:34,015
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you to the audience here in the Senedd in Cardiff, to you for watching and listening at home, and of course, to the seven politicians who've taken part in tonight's debate.

1152
01:27:34,035 --> 01:27:35,837
[SPEAKER_04]: From me, Nick Robinson, goodnight.

